               <p>1586. <persName id="def1-1586-18350615" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1586-18350615" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1586-18350615" type="surname" value="BURFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1586-18350615" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE BURFIELD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18350615-1586-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18350615-1586-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18350615-1586-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp>for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350615-name-1266" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1266" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1266" type="surname" value="ADAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1266" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH ADAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a master baker. The prisoner was in my service six weeks—he took out bread—it was his duty to return an account, when he came home, of the money he might receive from the customers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he not state that he had lost the money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; he sent his wife—she said she had but a half-crown; if I would take that, he would come to work at twelve o'clock—I said, "If he is a just man let him come and settle his accounts"—I did not refuse to take the half-crown unless I had the whole.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came his wife to come and offer you the half-crown? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know, unless it was that I should not take the law—she ten<lb></lb>dered me a letter in his own handwriting, saying he was gone off—it was about seven o'clock in the evening of the 27th of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350615-name-1267" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1267" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1267" type="surname" value="RODDA"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1267" type="given" value="LYDIA"></interp>LYDIA RODDA</persName>
                  </hi>. The prosecutor served me with bread—on the 27th of April I paid the prisoner 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. about eleven in the morning—I think it was some time in the forenoon—I paid it him for Mr. Adams.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350615-name-1268" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1268" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1268" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1268" type="given" value="SUSAN"></interp>SUSAN JOHNSON</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 27th of April I paid the prisoner 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. I be<lb></lb>lieve it was in the forenoon.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350615-name-1269" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1269" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1269" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350615-name-1269" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>STEPHEN TAYLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I paid the prisoner 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in the forenoon of the 27th of April.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JOSEPH ADAMS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was the prisoner's practice about settling his accounts? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between twelve and one in the day. He had generally done his work by that time—he did not come home that day—I never saw him till he was taken into custody—his wife came in the evening.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I met a few friends, who asked me to have some<lb></lb>thing to drink, and I had rather too much—I fell asleep—when I awoke I missed my money.</p>
               <p>
